{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The generated function signature matches the expected interface (parameter names, types, return type) specified in the description.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The failure boundary is the model’s real code-generation behavior: whether a real LLM reliably maps natural-language interface requirements to the correct signature. A deterministic stub can validate parser/validator wiring but can hide true signature-drift failures from model variability. Rejected lower level (Integration) because the behavior text is about the generated signature matching the NL spec, which is disqualified from pure wiring tests when model output quality is the target.","test_description":"Run the service with a real LLM on a prompt with strict signature constraints (names, typed params, return type), then parse the generated function and assert exact interface match; repeat across multiple runs/seeds to catch nondeterministic signature mismatch failures.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The generated implementation passes all provided test cases on the first or a subsequent attempt.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This behavior’s core failure can appear in real code execution and test-runner/process boundaries (compile/runtime errors, exit status handling, test invocation semantics), which in-process fakes can miss. Rejected higher level (Agentic) because this behavior can be validated with deterministic generated code fixtures (e.g., fail then pass) and does not require judging real model quality to verify pass-on-retry orchestration.","test_description":"Use the real execution path (actual test runner/subprocess and filesystem artifacts) with controlled generation outputs across attempts, and assert the service reports success once all real tests pass on attempt 1..3.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.45,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When tests fail, the refinement step includes the failure messages in the next LLM prompt so the model can learn from its mistakes.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The bug is at a local module handoff boundary: test-result collector -> prompt builder -> LLM client request payload. No real OS/network/subprocess is required, and correctness does not depend on model output quality, only that failure text is propagated into the next prompt. Rejected higher levels: System/Agentic are disqualified by behavior text focusing on prompt content inclusion, not infrastructure quirks or model judgment.","test_description":"Wire real prompt-construction and retry orchestration modules with a fake failing test result and a spy LLM client; assert the second-call prompt contains the exact failure messages (or normalized equivalent) from attempt 1.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The service stops after 3 failed attempts and returns a structured error with all three attempts and their test results.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is cross-module state/orchestration correctness: retry controller, attempt history accumulator, and error serializer. The real failure is often missing/overwritten attempt metadata between components. No real OS/network/subprocess is inherently required, and no real LLM quality judgment is required (deterministic fail fixtures suffice). Rejected higher levels because behavior text targets retry-state contract, not environment-dependent execution or AI quality.","test_description":"Use deterministic failing generation/test outcomes for three attempts through the real retry and error-formatting